My recent trip to England ‚Äì what a dream !! i'm so grateful to have been invited to speak in a place like the @cambridgeunion with so much rich history and I learned so much during my time there.

it‚Äôs clear the Queen has made such a great impact on the country as the longest-reigning British monarch to date. She‚Äôs an amazing leader !! Even in hard times like loss of her love, Prince Phillip, she leads with grace, strength, and wit.

Prince Charles has a huge vision for an environmentally conscious future ‚Äì we can all learn a lot here.

I also heard talk amongst locals about ending the monarchy ‚Äì but f*ck that! as an American, I've seen Prince William lead with great class. he‚Äôs a great representation of the of the future of the monarchy !!

And, Finally ‚Äì CAMBRIDGE!! - my visit with you exceeded my expectations. love you all s'much üíüüíü with Cambridge Union being a free speech society since 1815, i'm so happy I got to be real with u guys and u be real with me. I loved ur guys questions !!

i got to talk a lot about my mental health. as someone always in the spotlight, i have been open about my struggles ‚Äì and i believe there should be more focus on mental health by governments world-wide. people everywhere deserve greater access to the resources they need! even more amazing - I got to talk about a topic that's so close to my heart in a space where the late Princess Diana opened a greater conversation around mental health awareness. she was SO BRAVE to ignite a conversation that had been ignored throughout history!

I also loved talking about being an entrepreneur, sharing love, finding life and being yourself ! thanks for letting me enjoy being me !!

I am so grateful for the hard work of the millions of Americans that helped to build this country and create greater social & economic freedom. I am celebrating this beautiful #LaborDayWeekend with my family and closet friends. Thank you to all our workers, frontline workers and those in uniform who make this country what it is. We are indebted to you.¬†üëè

The men & women who have served their country with honor in & out of uniform should also be celebrated. To those who lost their lives in Afghanistan and those families who lost a service member, we will never ever forget you.¬†üá∫üá∏

I‚Äôve shared before that my fathers family is from Cuba and my father was the first to be born in this country on a military base in Key West, Florida. He came from a country where workers do not have the same rights we have here. I wish my father was alive today to share this weekend with my family, to meet my fianc√© Ben and to join us to honor hard working Americans who helped to build this country and those in the military who have also worked so hard to keep us free. Both he and my grandparents knew well how Cuba was a place where freedom was severely limited and today where the rights of its citizens and workers remain terribly oppressed. He taught me through his stories the importance of hard work and of living in a land where freedom reigns alive and how precious it is.

I am forever indebted to all of you who advocated for better working conditions and the brave souls who have worked and fought so hard to protect all of our freedoms in this country.¬†

I also believe one of the most important freedoms we have is our right to chose what happens to our bodies. Having an abortion is a deeply painful personal choice between a woman and her doctor. It is a freedom that should be maintained.¬†

This is not #handmaidstale. This is not #gilead. ‚ùå This is the United States, land of the free, where women should always have a choice about what happens to their bodies.¬†

So many worked so hard to protect our country‚Äôs freedoms, freedoms of all kinds. To me this means freedom to work in a safe environment, have equality, social justice, and ultimately the freedom of choice.

My father was the first in his family to be born in the United States on a military base in Key West. The remainder of his family was born in Cuba, I don‚Äôt know my family in Cuba. I‚Äôve never been able to travel and meet them. I don‚Äôt know if they are caught up in the violence right now, if they have food, water or medicine. I don‚Äôt know if they are safe or survived the pandemic which is surging across that beautiful island. What I do know is that Cuba needs our help. The Cuban people have reached a critical point in their ability to maintain a quality of life. Between the police violence, lack of basic human needs such as food and water, and the inability to control Covid outbreaks, the people are suffering and dying. We need to help them. They need international intervention. Please use your voice to bring awareness and ask the world to assist in the plight of the Cuban people. #cubalibre #sos

#mynaturalbeauty 

I know us girls love to put on makeup, not only for fun but sometimes to hide our insecurities...well, here is a photo of me without ANY makeup on my face. 

I took this photo while arriving to set this morning. Personally, I struggled with acne for a long time. I used to cry every night because I thought I looked so ugly. I used to read comments about my face, my skin, my nose, my eyes, and even my beauty marks people didn't approve of. 

Putting makeup over acne makes it so much worse. 

I know lots of my friends also struggle with acne and it's something you can't control. I know lots of people think others with acne are " dirty" or "don't take care of themselves". That is false.

My question to you is: Why should we be judged? 

Use #mynatrualbeauty & lets inspire every girl to be proud of what they look like and who they are. I love you guys. 

Oh and ps...If you don't accept me for my insecurities please get off my page :) #mynaturalbeauty
